    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/t2hoD.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3211603,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2711488,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2711488/holger",
                "reputation": 300991,
                "display_name": "Holger"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1434712001,
            "creation_date": 1434712001,
            "body": "<p>If you want the string representations to be glued together you may use<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>opts.stream().map(Object::toString).collect(Collectors.joining()));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>but if you just want get rid of the comma, i.e. keep a space as separator, you can customize it as<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>opts.stream().map(Object::toString).collect(Collectors.joining(\" \")));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or, if <em>obsolete<\/em> separators are you concern, i.e. you don\u2019t want separators between empty strings, use<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>opts.stream().map(Object::toString)\n    .filter(s-&gt;!s.isEmpty()).collect(Collectors.joining(\" \"))\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you miss the brackets, use either<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>opts.stream().map(Object::toString).collect(Collectors.joining(\" \", \"[\", \"]\"))\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>opts.stream().map(Object::toString)\n    .filter(s-&gt;!s.isEmpty()).collect(Collectors.joining(\" \", \"[\", \"]\"))\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 30936612,
            "question_id": 30936112
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/Z7UC0.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 23037,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 57448,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/57448/rahel-l%c3%bcthy",
                "reputation": 7047,
                "display_name": "Rahel L&#252;thy",
                "accept_rate": 71
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1434711850,
            "creation_date": 1434711850,
            "body": "<p>If you were using Java 8 <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Optional.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Optional<\/a>, it would look like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;Optional&lt;String&gt;&gt; opts = Arrays.asList(\n   Optional.of(\"bli\"),\n   Optional.&lt;String&gt;empty(),\n   Optional.of(\"bla\"));\n\nString result = opts.stream().filter(Optional::isPresent).map(Optional::get).collect(Collectors.joining(\", \"));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>resulting in \"bli, bla\" without any extra commas.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you can't use the official <code>Optional<\/code> class, you could maybe change your <code>Option<\/code> to behave similarly?<\/p>\n\n<p>BTW: With Java 9 you could even replace the awkward <code>filter(Optional::isPresent).map(Optional::get)<\/code> with <code>flatMap(Optional::stream)<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30936563,
            "question_id": 30936112
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://graph.facebook.com/100007829376909/picture?type=large",
                "account_id": 4763924,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3850595,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3850595/jordi-castilla",
                "reputation": 27069,
                "display_name": "Jordi Castilla",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1434713981,
            "creation_date": 1434710710,
            "body": "<p>I guess not a good idea to override <code>toString<\/code> of <code>ArrayList<\/code>, but you can create your own print function in some Utility class of your application:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static String myToString(List&lt;?&gt; list) {\n    StringBuilder stringList = new StringBuilder();\n    String delimiter = \" \";\n    for (int c = 0; c &lt; list.size(); c++) {\n        stringList.append(delimiter);\n        stringList.append(list.get(c));\n    }\n    return stringList.toString();\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 30936213,
            "question_id": 30936112,
            "last_edit_date": 1434713981
        }
    ],
